00:35:18,056 --> 00:35:21,417
And is everyone here familiar with Summer Street?

403
00:35:21,997 --> 00:35:25,077
So you've got South Street right along and parallel to the river.

404
00:35:25,557 --> 00:35:28,178
As you go toward Tufts, the next parallel street to it,

405
00:35:28,922 --> 00:35:36,968
is Summer Street, you go past that you have George, okay, Toro Avenue, as you probably know, is just one block long, goes between Summer and South.

406
00:35:38,909 --> 00:35:45,434
What is today Summer Street, beginning in the early 1830s, that was the Middlesex Canal.

407
00:35:46,215 --> 00:35:51,919
Summer Street follows exactly the path of the Middlesex Canal.

408
00:35:52,499 --> 00:35:58,003
And there was a bridge over that canal at Toro Ave, and another bridge over the canal at Main Street.

409
00:35:58,710 --> 00:36:01,351
So Toro Ave was pretty important.

410
00:36:02,332 --> 00:36:12,556
As best I can figure from the deeds, and I missed one day because I went to the courthouse and it was closed for snow about a week ago, but I'm going to go back tomorrow and I'd be glad to submit the detail.

411
00:36:12,596 --> 00:36:23,421
I've got my preliminary report here and I think by the end of the week I could give a council, you know, more detail and then you can decide what you'd like to put into a letter to Tufts.

412
00:36:24,101 --> 00:36:25,682
But here's the bottom line.

413
00:36:26,784 --> 00:36:32,085
The Toro family has largely been lost to Medford history.

414
00:36:32,386 --> 00:36:38,007
You go back to all the histories of Medford and you really find virtually nothing about them.

415
00:36:39,087 --> 00:36:48,590
Judah Toro was the most famous Jewish philanthropist in America in the 19th century.

416
00:36:49,352 --> 00:36:49,652
Okay?

417
00:36:49,692 --> 00:36:52,113
There are books about him in the Library of Congress.

418
00:36:52,193 --> 00:36:54,294
I've gotten scans of three of them.

419
00:36:54,994 --> 00:36:55,315
Okay?

420
00:36:55,615 --> 00:37:07,240
When he died in 1854, his will was so generous that it was published, not just around America, but in foreign countries as an inspiration to people.

421
00:37:07,640 --> 00:37:08,020
Okay?

422
00:37:09,060 --> 00:37:15,363
Now, nobody has really suspected that Judah Toro had a connection to Medford, because he lived in New Orleans.

423
00:37:16,692 --> 00:37:20,715
Funny thing, he grew up in Boston with his brother and sister.

424
00:37:21,495 --> 00:37:27,679
He ended up going down to New Orleans, handled that part of the family shipping and merchandise business.

425
00:37:28,200 --> 00:37:35,124
His brother Abraham handled the main part from Boston, but he built a second house in Medford.

426
00:37:36,605 --> 00:37:42,109
He paid $1,100 in 1808 to buy a major part of our neighborhood.

427
00:37:42,129 --> 00:37:43,690
That was a lot of money back then.

428
00:37:44,783 --> 00:37:54,971
He had a house, which should be a historic landmark, but it was torn down in the early 1900s to build a series of apartment houses.

429
00:37:56,231 --> 00:38:03,157
That's what the Medford historical record volumes say from 100 years ago.

430
00:38:03,517 --> 00:38:07,800
Those are probably the triple-deckers that are on Toro Avenue right along South.

431
00:38:07,840 --> 00:38:08,841
You have a set of four of them.

432
00:38:09,581 --> 00:38:14,365
But there's more, obviously, we need to nail down, but the point is that

433
00:38:14,952 --> 00:38:27,659
Abraham Toro died an untimely death in 1822 when he went to the annual military parade in Boston and a cannon shot explosion spooked his horse.

434
00:38:28,359 --> 00:38:32,642
He ended up taking a hard fall, compound fracture of his leg.

435
00:38:33,462 --> 00:38:39,686
It turned into gangrene and he declared that he'd rather enter heaven with two legs than one.

436
00:38:39,806 --> 00:38:43,928
So he did not let the surgeons at Mass General Hospital amputate.

437
00:38:44,687 --> 00:38:53,251
He himself had endowed Mass General Hospital with so much money that according to a history in the Library of Congress, it made the director's head spin.

438
00:38:54,011 --> 00:38:58,634
His brother Judah, okay, then became owner.

439
00:38:59,744 --> 00:39:01,405
of the land in our neighborhood.

440
00:39:02,166 --> 00:39:03,206
I don't think anybody's ever known that.

441
00:39:03,226 --> 00:39:07,749
There's nothing in the history books, but it's there in the Middlesex Registry of Deeds.

442
00:39:08,210 --> 00:39:19,297
And surprisingly, although he spent most of his time in New Orleans, he and his sister Rebecca, who lived in New York, they bought more land to fill out their land holdings.

443
00:39:19,918 --> 00:39:24,301
During the 10 to 12 years after their brother's death, and then starting around 1836 to 1840,

444
00:39:26,502 --> 00:39:29,605
They sold it off, it got subdivided, and it's what you have now.

445
00:39:30,505 --> 00:39:30,926
Okay?

446
00:39:31,586 --> 00:39:32,927
Now, the Tufts connection.

447
00:39:34,328 --> 00:39:47,299
Judah Turow's will was most famous, and his whole life of philanthropy was famous for being the biggest benefactor of the Unitarian Church in New Orleans.

448
00:39:47,479 --> 00:39:49,481
The pastor of that church was a good friend of his.

449
00:39:50,378 --> 00:40:08,373
being the biggest benefactor, and it was in his will also, of the Jewish synagogue in Newport, Rhode Island, which was the first synagogue in the British colonies, and his dad had been the rabbi there right at the start of the Revolutionary War, and also Mass General Hospital.

450
00:40:09,134 --> 00:40:12,016
When you think of Tufts,

451
00:40:13,084 --> 00:40:18,968
what was tough started at, as it was the college of the Unitarian Church in Massachusetts, okay?

452
00:40:19,428 --> 00:40:41,361
All we're doing here is really asking that what is probably the oldest surviving house on Touro family land, even if it was people after them that built it, plus the land itself, which is the only, you know, nice surviving residential, you know, grassy area other than the public park, which we really appreciate, beautiful park, okay?

453
00:40:43,244 --> 00:41:00,602
that that be somehow memorialized, not only for the architecture, which is impressive and old and historic, and that in itself would be ample reason, but this is to memorialize somebody who, he was one of the most important landowners in Medford.

454
00:41:00,662 --> 00:41:04,205
His brother was one of the most important citizens and a good friend of Governor Brooks.

455
00:41:06,161 --> 00:41:08,182
And there's just a great story to be told here.

456
00:41:08,542 --> 00:41:18,089
And in terms of the Jewish philanthropy aspect, Tufts is one of the biggest beneficiaries of generous Jewish philanthropy today.

457
00:41:18,169 --> 00:41:24,914
So, I mean, if this isn't a story that, you know, strikes somebody at Tufts, but frankly, they never had a chance to hear it.

458
00:41:25,695 --> 00:41:27,916
So, I'd be glad to give the material to counsel.

459
00:41:28,617 --> 00:41:32,720
If you want to give it to Tufts, I think somebody over there would pay attention.

