Or is this something that was more driven through feedback that you've received from the constituency and from the conversations that we've had?

814
01:15:18,469 --> 01:15:24,952
Or is this something that, you know, there's multiple working parts and working people that are actually working on a working group of some sort?

815
01:15:26,233 --> 01:15:27,553
This was my resolution.

816
01:15:27,773 --> 01:15:29,374
So this was strictly my resolution.

817
01:15:30,074 --> 01:15:37,537
I did have a conversation knowing that a home rule petition needs to be approved by both the executive branch and the legislative branch.

818
01:15:37,998 --> 01:15:42,820
So I did have a conversation with the mayor regarding what some of her concerns would be.

819
01:15:43,561 --> 01:15:50,184
And I think this is a compilation of getting the mayor's office and my resolution together.

820
01:15:50,264 --> 01:15:58,368
So when we eventually put this all together that we don't have to worry that the executive branch is not on board.

821
01:15:58,968 --> 01:16:02,290
And I think that goes a long way in moving this forward.

822
01:16:03,010 --> 01:16:06,972
And the city solicitor helped me draft some of the language

823
01:16:07,669 --> 01:16:12,852
especially some of the concerns we had regarding how should it be worded and so forth.

824
01:16:13,492 --> 01:16:24,718
Because this is a legal document and my request is actually for this to be sent once we approve it to the city solicitor so he can draft a home rule petition, which is a legal document.

825
01:16:25,399 --> 01:16:30,241
And that home rule petition, once it's signed by the mayor, will then come back to the council.

826
01:16:30,662 --> 01:16:32,483
So like I said, this is only the first step.

827
01:16:33,183 --> 01:16:37,005
It still has to get approved by this body, go to the mayor,

828
01:16:37,405 --> 01:16:39,646
And then the mayor has to approve it, then come back to the council.

829
01:16:39,886 --> 01:16:42,828
And then come out in the same form it went in as and be approved by the council.

830
01:16:42,848 --> 01:16:43,428
Right, right.

831
01:16:44,028 --> 01:16:50,311
And then hopefully the state legislature will feel that this has to be acted upon quickly also.

832
01:16:50,331 --> 01:16:51,532
Thank you, council.

833
01:16:52,973 --> 01:16:53,493
Councilor Knight.

834
01:16:54,133 --> 01:16:54,434
That was it.

835
01:16:55,594 --> 01:16:57,015
Chair recognizes Councilor Caviello.

836
01:16:57,175 --> 01:16:58,115
Thank you, Mr. President.

837
01:16:58,496 --> 01:17:06,980
I really like Councilor Scott Pelley's suggestion of bringing in the call on Senate, where this hasn't been done in so many years, and this group is

838
01:17:07,983 --> 01:17:20,647
has been doing it for other cities that may help us get a better handle on what actually needs to be done and more realistic goals than maybe what we know.

839
01:17:21,087 --> 01:17:25,708
And they may offer some better suggestions going forward than maybe we were even looking for in the beginning.

840
01:17:30,450 --> 01:17:31,250
Thank you, Councillor.

841
01:17:33,420 --> 01:17:33,760
Welcome.

842
01:17:34,120 --> 01:17:35,681
Please state your name and address for the record.

843
01:17:36,121 --> 01:17:38,481
Will Walker, 9 Piedmont Road, Medford.

844
01:17:41,042 --> 01:17:45,303
First, I'd like to thank Councilor Marks for bringing this resolution forward.

845
01:17:45,443 --> 01:17:51,385
The charter review process that has been underway, I think, has picked up a great deal of steam.

846
01:17:51,745 --> 01:18:00,867
And one of the concerns that those of us who have been working on moving it forward have had is that we would like to be doing this with the cooperation of city government.

847
01:18:01,687 --> 01:18:03,389
In particular, the Mayor's Office and the City Council.

848
01:18:03,449 --> 01:18:08,673
So we're really grateful to see that that progress is actually happening.

849
01:18:09,773 --> 01:18:22,443
And recognizing that having multiple and concurrent processes going forward on this can lead to some conflicts and misunderstandings that can confuse especially the citizens as they try to make sense of all of this.

850
01:18:25,696 --> 01:18:41,381
I understand that this is going to go to Committee of the Whole if it goes as is, and that that committee would then deliberate on what the actual wording of the thing to be sent to the state legislature would be, and then presumably it would come back to this body to be approved and sent over to the mayor and so forth.

851
01:18:45,122 --> 01:18:47,563
Whatever results from the Committee of the Whole goes to the mayor first.

852
01:18:48,423 --> 01:18:49,203
Okay, and then it comes back?

853
01:18:49,223 --> 01:18:53,345
The mayor would have to approve it, then it would come back to us, and then it would be sent to the state legislature.

854
01:18:56,008 --> 01:19:11,955
With that in mind, as a policy scholar and as someone with a graduate degree in city planning and municipal policy in particular, there are a couple of things that I would request that the committee of the whole considers.

855
01:19:12,655 --> 01:19:14,756
One of these has already been discussed, the five change cap.

856
01:19:16,035 --> 01:19:24,059
The problem with a cap like that is that it makes the perhaps idealistic assumption that there are only five things that need to be changed.

857
01:19:25,039 --> 01:19:26,360
It's a 30-year-old document.

858
01:19:27,600 --> 01:19:33,303
A lot has changed in 30 years, as other people have commented, and that limitation can actually wind up hamstringing the process.

859
01:19:34,453 --> 01:19:38,794
It was mentioned earlier that there was a concern that there would be five ballot questions.

860
01:19:39,274 --> 01:19:46,716
My understanding of how the charter review process goes is once that commission has produced the product of its work, that product is actually a new charter.

861
01:19:47,576 --> 01:19:57,979
And then that charter becomes a single ballot question in a yes or no fashion that the voters either approve that new charter, in which case it replaces the old charter, or they do not approve that new charter and the status quo is retained.

862
01:19:59,323 --> 01:20:12,751
In that being the case, and the city solicitor would know better than I, that being the case, there isn't any real worry necessarily that there would be so many ballot questions that it could blow the ballot or anything like that.

863
01:20:13,552 --> 01:20:22,638
There is, I agree, a concern about getting the job done in six months and getting a thorough job done in six months, but I think that the time limit

864
01:20:23,138 --> 01:20:31,532
The sense of urgency there is less important than getting it done and done well.

865
01:20:31,552 --> 01:20:35,718
I had a list of things that I wanted to talk about.

866
01:20:35,778 --> 01:20:37,100
Many of them have already been addressed.

867
01:20:38,585 --> 01:20:43,010
One clarification that has not been addressed is there are multiple paths to charter review.

868
01:20:43,130 --> 01:20:47,716
One of them is through the petition process that has been going around and currently, at last count, have 1500 signatures.

869
01:20:48,497 --> 01:20:49,838
It assuredly has more than that now.

870
01:20:51,600 --> 01:20:56,206
That process winds up having, as I understand it, a greater authority

871
01:20:56,947 --> 01:21:09,378
to make changes to the charter than would an appointed body put forward by the city council or the mayor, which would, for obvious reasons of conflict of interest, not be able to, for example, extend city council terms indefinitely into the future, and so on and so forth.

872
01:21:12,480 --> 01:21:29,911
home rule petition originates in the City Council and would have to be approved by the Mayor, residents of Medford should have clarified for them whether or not the elected body that would come from this process would be constrained as would an appointed body by the City Council or by the Mayor.

873
01:21:30,351 --> 01:21:39,737
In other words, is this merely a novel appointment process and this seven-member body that Councilor Marks proposes here would be

874
01:21:40,237 --> 01:21:44,980
unable to make changes to, for example, term limits or other things that would otherwise be restricted?

875
01:21:45,360 --> 01:21:53,045
Or do they have, as an elected body, the full power and freedom that would be afforded to the body that would result from the petition process?

876
01:21:54,906 --> 01:22:04,912
There is a stipulation in here, and I'm not sure how binding the language of the resolution is on the committee of the whole when they consider the document that they produce on that.

877
01:22:06,083 --> 01:22:15,894
But there is a language in here that says, at a minimum, we have this change requiring that the city charter be amended to include this periodic review process.

878
01:22:15,914 --> 01:22:23,162
And that review process involves an appointed committee, presumably appointed by the city council or mayor, that would then perform that charter review.

879
01:22:23,302 --> 01:22:27,687
That body would most assuredly be limited in its power, which probably makes sense for the periodic process.

880
01:22:28,071 --> 01:22:50,180
But the question is, because of the language, at minimum, does that minimum mean here that it has to be exactly that, an appointed committee, or if the seven-member committee decides that actually they would rather that that period of review be done by an elected commission separate from city government, would that meet the standard in this language of the minimum, right?

881
01:22:50,220 --> 01:22:54,442
Is that considered a greater or lesser effort for the purposes of this resolution?

882
01:22:59,057 --> 01:23:00,137
Last thing, separate ballot questions.

883
01:23:00,157 --> 01:23:01,478
Yeah, that's basically what I have.

884
01:23:02,898 --> 01:23:09,441
I understand that this is a draft-in-living document that Councilor Marks just put forward, and I think it's a very commendable effort.

885
01:23:09,481 --> 01:23:11,902
Certainly, I'm very interested in seeing the final product.

886
01:23:12,482 --> 01:23:18,204
The last word that I have on this is that charter review and the processes around it are very, very technical.

887
01:23:18,865 --> 01:23:27,568
They're very complex, and they are often very confusing to people who don't study issues of constitutional law and policy structures directly.

888
01:23:28,508 --> 01:23:34,589
And especially given that the Massachusetts state law has all of these procedures that look like one another but don't wind up with the same outcomes.

889
01:23:35,289 --> 01:23:55,353
To the extent possible that citizens and voters can be informed of what the meaning and significance of this process would be, I think that that would be very useful, especially to those of us who are organizing citizens and gathering signatures to determine whether or not we are satisfied that this process would be sufficient or whether or not we think that we still need something more.

890
01:23:55,793 --> 01:23:56,033
Thank you.

891
01:23:59,365 --> 01:24:00,085
Councilor Max.

892
01:24:01,026 --> 01:24:02,907
Just, uh, I can't answer all the questions.

893
01:24:02,947 --> 01:24:07,090
I think maybe some of them might be best directed to the city solicitor.

894
01:24:07,890 --> 01:24:22,719
Uh, but, uh, regarding the, uh, one question, uh, the gentleman had regarding the, uh, sentence that says at a minimum, an amendment to the present city charter instituting an appointed committee whose purpose will be to conduct periodic review of the city charter.

895
01:24:23,380 --> 01:24:28,243
Um, I think, uh, we felt that, um,

896
01:24:28,835 --> 01:24:40,082
no matter what happens with the results and the recommendations that will appear on the ballot, that that one provision automatically is going to be a ballot question.

897
01:24:40,242 --> 01:24:52,070
That, I think everyone I've spoken to feels that the one omission when this charter was changed back some years ago from E to A government was the lack of a provision that said this shall be reviewed.

898
01:24:52,913 --> 01:24:57,856
And I think at the very, and that's why we worded it that way, can it be changed a little bit?

899
01:24:57,956 --> 01:25:03,960
Probably, but we wanted to make sure at a minimum that was going to be part of whatever questions appear on the ballot.

900
01:25:04,540 --> 01:25:06,382
And then you mentioned about the elected body.

901
01:25:07,682 --> 01:25:12,125
This is a seven member body that's elected by the people.

902
01:25:12,846 --> 01:25:19,610
So they will have every authority to go in and make any changes to the current city charter.

903
01:25:20,197 --> 01:25:25,599
And that would include ward representation, term limits, anything that exists under the charter.

904
01:25:25,999 --> 01:25:30,400
So there's no restrictions within this elected body.

905
01:25:31,140 --> 01:25:36,482
So I don't want anyone to think that this is an elected body that we're saying they're elected, but guess what?

906
01:25:36,522 --> 01:25:37,142
They're really not.

907
01:25:37,582 --> 01:25:38,082
They're really not.

908
01:25:38,102 --> 01:25:39,403
They're just people we're putting in there.

909
01:25:39,783 --> 01:25:43,184
These are elected people that run for this particular seat.

910
01:25:43,517 --> 01:25:53,104
and they'll have all the duly regulated authority to make it move forward charter review questions in the following year.

911
01:25:53,604 --> 01:25:56,666
So whatever recommendations they have, they're not going to be reviewed again.

912
01:25:56,967 --> 01:25:58,047
There's no review body.

913
01:25:58,268 --> 01:26:01,490
There's no one saying, wow, we don't like that, or we don't like that, or guess what?

914
01:26:01,530 --> 01:26:02,991
The council really doesn't like that.

915
01:26:03,351 --> 01:26:07,174
They appear on the ballot automatically for a decision by the people.

916
01:26:07,854 --> 01:26:12,336
And it's my understanding, I know the gentleman mentioned that it could be done.

917
01:26:12,456 --> 01:26:18,018
One way is to have just a revision of the charter, and now you have a new charter.

918
01:26:18,138 --> 01:26:27,582
So if this was plan A, now we have this plan A. But I'm also under the impression we can offer particular ballot questions, revising the current plan A form of government.

919
01:26:28,103 --> 01:26:30,764
And that's the impression I got from the city solicitor.

920
01:26:31,164 --> 01:26:35,826
So that was part of the reasoning why, after so many years, that we didn't want

921
01:26:36,410 --> 01:26:42,492
leave it open-ended, but because we thought there'd be a slew of ballot questions, and that may get confusing.

922
01:26:43,172 --> 01:26:52,535
So in my opinion, but like I said from the beginning, I'm not opposed to removing that language regarding the restrictions on the number of amendments that could be offered.

923
01:26:53,036 --> 01:26:53,876
Thank you, Counselor.

924
01:26:54,596 --> 01:26:55,316
Ma'am, welcome.

925
01:26:55,336 --> 01:26:56,837
Please state your name and address for the record.

926
01:26:57,412 --> 01:26:59,834
Hi, I'm Cheryl Rodriguez at 21 Park Street.

